{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9bm8l8/include_key_in_results_of_sql_statement_that/", "text": "As found as this [link](https://www.w3resource.com/sql/aggregate-functions/min-with-group-by.php)\n\nThe statement is \n\nSELECT cust_city, cust_country, MIN(outstanding_amt) \n\nFROM customer \n\nGROUP BY cust_country, cust_city ;\n\nThe results give the minimum value for city and customer, however I also want to find the key for this row as well. When I add it to the SELECT statement it gives an error. How can I display other columns?", "score": 1, "comments": [{"body": "Try using a join.\n    \n    SELECT [other attributes], outstanding_amt, cust_city, cust_country\n        FROM customer as t1\n        INNER JOIN (\n            SELECT cust_city, cust_country, MIN(outstanding_amt) as outstanding_amt\n            FROM customer\n            GROUP BY cust_country, cust_city) as t2\n            ON t1.price = t2.price AND t1.cust_city = t2.cust_city AND t1.cust_country = t2.cust_country;\n\nSomething along those lines should do it", "id": "e546d29", "replies": []}], "title": "Include key in results of SQL statement that groups by two columns"}